pattern of continuity and isolated change, the book strongly nuances claims that neo-liberalism, globalization or a rise in populism have been its causes. References to these trends have impacted upon French politics to varying extents, Smith argues; however, France continues to be dominated by issues which are specific to the country and linked to its deep societal structures and history. Smith provides a comprehensive account of French society and politics and in doing so proposes an insightful analytical framework applicable to the comparative analysis of other nations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aEuropean Uniomn.  aFrance.  aglobalisation.  ainstitutions.  amaterialism.  aneo-liberalism.  apolitical work.  apopulism.  apower relations.  athe State.1 aSmith, Andy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615424840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526154248423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526154248/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles